SIMPLE: solemnity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Solemnity
<hw>So*lem"ni*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Solemnities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>solemnitas</ets>, <ets>solennitas</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>solennit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, <ets>solemnit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, OF. also
<ets>sollempnit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A rite or
ceremony performed with religious reverence; religious or ritual
ceremony; <as>as, the <ex>solemnity</ex> of a funeral, a
sacrament</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great was the cause; our old <qex>solemnities</qex>⟦br⟧
From no blind zeal or fond tradition rise,⟦br⟧
But saved from death, our Argives yearly pay⟦br⟧
These grateful honors to the god of day.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>ceremony adapted to impress with awe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The forms and <qex>solemnities</qex> of the last judgment.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterburry.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Ceremoniousness; impressiveness; seriousness; grave
earnestness; formal dignity; gravity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With much glory and great <qex>solemnity</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The statelines and gravity of the Spaniards shows itself in the
<qex>solemnity</qex> of their language.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These promises were often made with great <qex>solemnity</qex> and
confirmed with an oath.</q> <rj><qau>J. Edwards.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence, affected gravity or seriousness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Solemnity</qex> 's a cover for a sot.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Solemn state or feeling; awe or reverence; also,
that which produces such a feeling; <as>as, the <ex>solemnity</ex> of an
audience; the <ex>solemnity</ex> of Westminster Abbey</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A solemn or formal observance;
proceeding according to due form; the formality which is necessary to
render a thing done valid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solemnizate</ent>⟦br⟧
